  "text": "CORRESPONDENCE 12 November 2024 By Nick G. Vary1 \u0026 Erika L. Lorshbough2 Alexander J. Stokes University of Hawaii, Honolulu, Hawaii, USA. Nick G. Vary InterConnect Support Group, Bethesda, Maryland, USA. Erika L. Lorshbough interACT: Advocates for Intersex Youth, Sudbury, Massachusetts, USA. Intersex people such as ourselves — who do not fit biologically into a male–female sex binary — make up 1.7–2.3% of the population, or more than 188 million people worldwide (M. Blackless et al. Am. J. Hum. Biol. 12, 151–166; 2000). Yet systemic biases mean that our experiences are mostly reduced to case reports and curiosities. Barriers to the integration of intersex research and of individuals’ experiences into broader scientific understanding must be dismantled. Access options Access Nature and 54 other Nature Portfolio journals Get Nature+, our best-value online-access subscription $29.99 / 30 days cancel any time Subscribe to this journal Receive 51 print issues and online access $199.00 per year only $3.90 per issue Rent or buy this articlePrices vary by article typefrom$1.95to$39.95Prices may be subject to local taxes which are calculated during checkout Additional access options: Log in Learn about institutional subscriptions Read our FAQs Contact customer support Nature 635, 290 (2024) doi: https://doi.org/10.1038/d41586-024-03662-1 Competing Interests A.J.S. declares the following sources of funding: 1. NIH AIM AHEAD DICB (Grant No: 1OT2OD032581 Project Leader STOKES); 2. NSF INCLUDES ALL-SPICE (Grant No: 2217242, COPI: Stokes); 3. NSF Scholarship in STEM (S-STEM) (Grant No: 2221448, PI: Stokes); 4. NSF Pacific Excellence in Analytics (Grant No: 2030654, COPI: Stokes); 6. NSF RII Track-1: Change Hawaii (Grant No: 2149133, KP: Stokes); and 7. NSF SCIPE: Cyberinfrastructure Pacific Professionals (KP:Stokes) (Grant No: 2329401). Related Articles We need more-nuanced approaches to exploring sex and gender in research Neglecting sex and gender in research is 